00:00:07.151 --> 00:00:08.650
JOHN ORWANT: My
name is John Orwant.

00:00:08.650 --> 00:00:13.560
I'm with the Google Cambridge
Tea Party Republicans Club.

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:18.120
And it's a pleasure and an honor
to introduce our guest today--

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:21.610
a man whose fame rises to a
level of the kind that renders

00:00:21.610 --> 00:00:25.110
the standard introduction
pattern completely obsolete.

00:00:25.110 --> 00:00:28.090
I could tell you
about his 123 books.

00:00:28.090 --> 00:00:29.106
I counted.

00:00:29.106 --> 00:00:30.480
The seven books
have been written

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:34.812
about him, the 38 doctoral--
honorary doctoral degrees--

00:00:34.812 --> 00:00:35.770
that he's been granted.

00:00:35.770 --> 00:00:38.150
I could tell you about
the species of bee

00:00:38.150 --> 00:00:40.520
that has been named after him.

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:43.960
Instead, I'm actually going to
talk about tenure, because it's

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:47.230
actually the thing
I think of first

00:00:47.230 --> 00:00:50.610
when I think about
our guest today.

00:00:50.610 --> 00:00:53.621
We tend to think of tenure
today as an entitlement.

00:00:53.621 --> 00:00:54.120
Right?

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:56.530
So, professors--
they work really hard

00:00:56.530 --> 00:00:58.190
for some amount of time.

00:00:58.190 --> 00:01:01.450
And then they're kind of
granted this lifetime protection

00:01:01.450 --> 00:01:03.960
from being fired.

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:07.300
And, the institution of
tenure has been around

00:01:07.300 --> 00:01:08.780
for many decades.

00:01:08.780 --> 00:01:13.570
It really started to solidify
around the time of the McCarthy

00:01:13.570 --> 00:01:17.340
era, where a lot of
professors in this country

00:01:17.340 --> 00:01:19.640
were being asked to
take oaths of loyalty

00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:21.760
as part of the
anti-communist fervor that

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:23.500
was sweeping the nation.

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:26.030
And it wasn't that the
University administrations

00:01:26.030 --> 00:01:28.110
wanted them to take those oaths.

00:01:28.110 --> 00:01:29.080
They were worried.

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:32.250
The universities were worried
about pressure from government.

00:01:32.250 --> 00:01:34.707
They were worried about
wealthy donors saying,

00:01:34.707 --> 00:01:36.665
I'll give you this check
for a million dollars,

00:01:36.665 --> 00:01:40.390
but you have to fire that
professor over there.

00:01:40.390 --> 00:01:43.130
And so that's why
universities kind of lept

00:01:43.130 --> 00:01:45.240
into this institution
with gusto.

00:01:45.240 --> 00:01:46.740
And yet, when you
look at professors

00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:49.900
today, they very rarely
take advantage of tenure

00:01:49.900 --> 00:01:52.864
to speak on popular views.

00:01:52.864 --> 00:01:54.530
But of course, our
guest today, I think,

00:01:54.530 --> 00:01:58.300
is the world's best
example of doing that.

00:01:58.300 --> 00:02:01.290
And I think that getting
tenure perhaps today

00:02:01.290 --> 00:02:02.980
should come with
a mild obligation

00:02:02.980 --> 00:02:05.620
to speak truth to power.

00:02:05.620 --> 00:02:07.890
So anyway, with that,
ladies and gentlemen,

00:02:07.890 --> 00:02:12.330
I want to introduce a man who is
to the left of Julian Assange,

00:02:12.330 --> 00:02:16.010
but with a less restrictive--
but with fewer travel

00:02:16.010 --> 00:02:17.867
restrictions-- Noam Chomsky.

00:02:17.867 --> 00:02:20.302
[APPLAUSE]

