00:12:57.570 --> 00:13:00.790
Switching gears a
little bit, what

00:13:00.790 --> 00:13:03.850
is the most interesting insight
the science of linguistics

00:13:03.850 --> 00:13:06.290
has revealed, but that
the public at large

00:13:06.290 --> 00:13:10.322
seems to not know
about or appreciate?

00:13:10.322 --> 00:13:18.490
Well, there are a number of
dogmas about language, which

00:13:18.490 --> 00:13:22.100
I think are being
systematically refuted.

00:13:22.100 --> 00:13:24.700
And they're held by
linguists, too, I should say.

00:13:24.700 --> 00:13:28.000
Not just in the general public,
which are probably false,

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:33.650
which I think are being
undermined by current research.

00:13:33.650 --> 00:13:34.960
This is a minority view.

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:36.470
I'm not speaking
for the profession.

00:13:39.060 --> 00:13:41.590
The introductory
comments said that I'm

00:13:41.590 --> 00:13:46.710
supposed to be a contrarian,
so I try to keep to that.

00:13:46.710 --> 00:13:49.290
But for example, one
general assumption

00:13:49.290 --> 00:13:55.290
about language-- almost
a dogma in philosophy.

00:13:55.290 --> 00:13:59.230
Common understanding, the
linguistics of psychology,

00:13:59.230 --> 00:14:04.070
is that language is primarily
a means of communication,

00:14:04.070 --> 00:14:08.240
and that it evolved as a
means of communication.

00:14:08.240 --> 00:14:11.360
Probably, that's totally false.

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:17.620
It seems that language is
evolved and is designed

00:14:17.620 --> 00:14:23.170
as a mode of creating
and interpreting thought.

00:14:23.170 --> 00:14:25.870
It's a system of
thought, basically.

00:14:25.870 --> 00:14:28.430
It can be used to communicate.

00:14:28.430 --> 00:14:31.360
Everything people do can
be used to communicate.

00:14:31.360 --> 00:14:34.320
You can communicate
by your hairstyle,

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:36.660
style of walk, everything.

00:14:36.660 --> 00:14:39.320
And yes, language can
be used to communicate,

00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:41.930
but it doesn't seem to
be part of its design.

00:14:41.930 --> 00:14:44.620
It's design seems to
be radically different,

00:14:44.620 --> 00:14:47.920
and in fact, even seems to
undermine communication.

00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:50.900
If you look carefully at
the structure of language,

00:14:50.900 --> 00:14:56.480
you find case after case, right
at the core of language design,

00:14:56.480 --> 00:15:00.160
where there are
conflicts between what

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:02.830
would be efficient
for communication,

00:15:02.830 --> 00:15:08.160
and what is efficient for the
specific biological design

00:15:08.160 --> 00:15:09.260
of language.

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:12.940
And in every case that's
known, communicative efficiency

00:15:12.940 --> 00:15:14.770
is sacrificed.

00:15:14.770 --> 00:15:17.100
It just isn't a consideration.

00:15:17.100 --> 00:15:20.830
I think that's a
conclusion that has

00:15:20.830 --> 00:15:23.370
very widespread significance.

00:15:23.370 --> 00:15:26.830
In order to establish it, you
have to look at technical work.

00:15:26.830 --> 00:15:28.750
It's not the kind
of thing you can

00:15:28.750 --> 00:15:33.160
explain in two
minutes of exposition.

00:15:33.160 --> 00:15:34.540
But it's not profound.

00:15:34.540 --> 00:15:35.745
It's not quantum physics.

00:15:35.745 --> 00:15:37.370
A half an hour would
certainly suffice.

00:15:37.370 --> 00:15:40.460
Suppliers And I think
it's a pretty far-reaching

00:15:40.460 --> 00:15:42.160
consequence.

00:15:42.160 --> 00:15:45.440
Another general
belief about language,

00:15:45.440 --> 00:15:51.020
again, almost a dogma in all the
relevant fields-- philosophy,

00:15:51.020 --> 00:15:54.840
linguistics, and so on--
is that the meaningful,

00:15:54.840 --> 00:15:57.360
the minimal meaningful
elements in language,

00:15:57.360 --> 00:16:00.870
sort of word-like
things, pick out

00:16:00.870 --> 00:16:04.100
entities in the
extra-mental world.

00:16:04.100 --> 00:16:08.970
So the word, say, river
picks out the Charles River,

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:13.240
and so on-- something that
a physicist could identify.

00:16:13.240 --> 00:16:16.410
That turns out to be
true for animal systems--

00:16:16.410 --> 00:16:18.700
animal communication systems.

00:16:18.700 --> 00:16:23.490
The symbols that appear-- the
actions that are carried out--

00:16:23.490 --> 00:16:27.560
do apparently have a
one to one correlation

00:16:27.560 --> 00:16:31.640
with mind independent events.

00:16:31.640 --> 00:16:35.120
So some particular
call of a monkey

00:16:35.120 --> 00:16:38.490
will be related to
leaves fluttering,

00:16:38.490 --> 00:16:44.210
predators coming, sort of-- I'm
hungry, some hormonal change.

00:16:44.210 --> 00:16:46.550
It's just not true of language.

00:16:46.550 --> 00:16:49.690
Linguistic elements do
not have that property.

00:16:49.690 --> 00:16:52.712
Actually, this was
understood by Aristotle.

00:16:52.712 --> 00:16:55.800
It was understood in the
17th and 18th centuries.

00:16:55.800 --> 00:16:57.710
Interesting work on it.

00:16:57.710 --> 00:17:03.710
The entities that we construct
in our communiques, discourse,

00:17:03.710 --> 00:17:08.720
expression, interpretation--
are largely mental-- partially,

00:17:08.720 --> 00:17:10.359
mental object.

00:17:10.359 --> 00:17:12.540
There are ways in
which they are--

00:17:12.540 --> 00:17:16.170
modes in which we
interpret phenomena.

00:17:16.170 --> 00:17:20.424
But they don't pick out
entities in the world

00:17:20.424 --> 00:17:24.010
that a natural
scientist could identify

00:17:24.010 --> 00:17:26.359
without looking into our minds.

00:17:26.359 --> 00:17:28.670
That tells us a lot about
the nature of language,

00:17:28.670 --> 00:17:32.490
and about our own nature.

00:17:32.490 --> 00:17:36.590
Language is the
core human property.

00:17:36.590 --> 00:17:38.330
And this was
understood by Darwin,

00:17:38.330 --> 00:17:41.630
by a long tradition before him.

00:17:41.630 --> 00:17:44.700
And it's very different from
the way it's usually conceived.

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:49.300
I think those are among
really conclusions that

00:17:49.300 --> 00:17:51.670
have pretty widespread
significance.

00:17:51.670 --> 00:17:55.210
Let me stress again,
a very minority view.

00:17:55.210 --> 00:17:57.730
Very few linguists
would agree with this.

00:17:57.730 --> 00:18:02.309
But I think, over time, I
suspect it will become clear.

00:18:02.309 --> 00:18:03.580
OK.

00:18:03.580 --> 00:18:05.970
In hopes and prospects, you
mentioned your colleague

00:18:05.970 --> 00:18:08.986
Kenneth Hale and his work
with Native Americans.

00:18:08.986 --> 00:18:10.860
In your opinion, how
important is the problem

00:18:10.860 --> 00:18:12.340
of language extinction?

00:18:12.340 --> 00:18:14.870
That is, how important
is it for humanity

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:18.340
to preserve the current level
of linguistic diversity?

00:18:18.340 --> 00:18:23.200
Well, Ken Hale, who was a
friend of Anne's as well.

00:18:23.200 --> 00:18:28.570
The teacher was a fantastic
linguist and person, also.

00:18:28.570 --> 00:18:33.610
He worked extensively
with indigenous languages

00:18:33.610 --> 00:18:35.580
all over the world.

00:18:35.580 --> 00:18:37.170
Australia-- he was
one of the founders

00:18:37.170 --> 00:18:38.910
of Australian
linguistics-- worked

00:18:38.910 --> 00:18:42.230
with Native American
languages, Central American,

00:18:42.230 --> 00:18:44.210
African, and so on.

00:18:44.210 --> 00:18:48.610
And he did really amazing work,
but this particular aspect

00:18:48.610 --> 00:18:51.680
of his work was something
that greatly concerned

00:18:51.680 --> 00:18:55.490
and interested him--
trying to protect.

00:18:55.490 --> 00:18:58.050
And as he pointed
out, correctly,

00:18:58.050 --> 00:19:03.130
when a language
disappears, a lot is lost.

00:19:03.130 --> 00:19:07.130
A language is a repository
of cultural wealth.

00:19:07.130 --> 00:19:08.860
It's a way-- this
actually relates

00:19:08.860 --> 00:19:11.800
to what I was saying
before-- each language is

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:15.380
a way of understanding and
interpreting the world.

00:19:15.380 --> 00:19:18.150
It carries the
wealth of tradition

00:19:18.150 --> 00:19:24.440
in history, oral history,
which can be extremely rich.

00:19:24.440 --> 00:19:27.360
Take the Bible, for example.

00:19:27.360 --> 00:19:30.770
For years, that
was oral history,

00:19:30.770 --> 00:19:33.540
before anything
was written down.

00:19:33.540 --> 00:19:35.960
Homer is oral history.

00:19:35.960 --> 00:19:38.130
And that's all over the world.

00:19:38.130 --> 00:19:39.984
And we're losing those
treasures every time

00:19:39.984 --> 00:19:40.900
a language disappears.

00:19:40.900 --> 00:19:46.520
And for the people themselves,
they're losing their identity.

00:19:46.520 --> 00:19:51.670
If English disappeared, we would
lose our cultural identity,

00:19:51.670 --> 00:19:55.260
and the same is true if it's
a small group somewhere.

00:19:55.260 --> 00:19:57.840
Well, one of Ken's
achievements in this regard,

00:19:57.840 --> 00:20:04.280
which was quite spectacular,
was to take the language, which

00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:06.390
was one of the major
languages spoken

00:20:06.390 --> 00:20:10.100
right here before
the colonists came.

00:20:10.100 --> 00:20:12.270
Remember, the
United States is not

00:20:12.270 --> 00:20:15.190
an ordinary form of imperialism.

00:20:15.190 --> 00:20:18.900
The United States is a
secular colonial society.

00:20:18.900 --> 00:20:21.460
In fact, that's true
of the whole-- what's

00:20:21.460 --> 00:20:25.510
called the Anglo sphere,
the countries that grew out

00:20:25.510 --> 00:20:30.140
of Britain's
imperial domination.

00:20:30.140 --> 00:20:35.180
The United States, Canada,
Australia, mostly New Zealand--

00:20:35.180 --> 00:20:38.920
these are countries where
the settlers who came in

00:20:38.920 --> 00:20:42.850
didn't just run the country the
way the British did in India.

00:20:42.850 --> 00:20:45.700
British in India
provided the bureaucrats,

00:20:45.700 --> 00:20:49.120
you know, the officer
corps, and so on.

00:20:49.120 --> 00:20:52.480
But Indians ran the
country under British rule.

00:20:52.480 --> 00:20:56.270
Secular colonial societies
are different, like ours.

00:20:56.270 --> 00:20:58.530
If you go back to the founders
of the country-- like,

00:20:58.530 --> 00:21:00.330
say George Washington.

00:21:00.330 --> 00:21:03.680
He understood very well that
we have to, as he put it,

00:21:03.680 --> 00:21:06.220
extirpate the Iroquois.

00:21:06.220 --> 00:21:07.510
They're in our way.

00:21:07.510 --> 00:21:08.890
We have to wipe them out.

00:21:08.890 --> 00:21:11.500
They're and advanced
civilization.

00:21:11.500 --> 00:21:13.270
They, in fact, were
the basis for much

00:21:13.270 --> 00:21:15.480
of the American
constitutional system.

00:21:15.480 --> 00:21:16.950
But we had to extirpate them.

00:21:16.950 --> 00:21:18.400
They were in our way.

00:21:18.400 --> 00:21:21.800
Thomas Jefferson said,
we have to exterminate

00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:24.980
the native populations
because they're attacking us.

00:21:24.980 --> 00:21:26.340
And why are they attacking us?

00:21:26.340 --> 00:21:29.320
Well, because we're taking
everything away from them.

00:21:29.320 --> 00:21:31.020
He didn't say that.

00:21:31.020 --> 00:21:33.550
But in general, the
settler colonial societies

00:21:33.550 --> 00:21:37.360
have to pretty much exterminate
the indigenous populations,

00:21:37.360 --> 00:21:39.160
or else marginalize them.

00:21:39.160 --> 00:21:40.710
Well that's happened here.

00:21:40.710 --> 00:21:43.810
So where we're
sitting was a place

00:21:43.810 --> 00:21:46.990
where the indigenous
population was

00:21:46.990 --> 00:21:49.580
close to exterminated--
pretty close to it.

00:21:49.580 --> 00:21:51.950
There are survivors.

00:21:51.950 --> 00:21:55.290
One of the major languages
spoken was one Wampanoag.

00:21:55.290 --> 00:21:57.660
It hadn't been
spoken for a century.

00:21:57.660 --> 00:22:00.290
The last speaker
was a century ago.

00:22:00.290 --> 00:22:07.330
Ken, and some students, and a
woman from the Wampanoag tribe,

00:22:07.330 --> 00:22:09.970
which still exists,
Jessie Little Doe,

00:22:09.970 --> 00:22:14.650
managed to reconstruct
the language using

00:22:14.650 --> 00:22:17.710
comparative evidence
from other languages,

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:21.780
and missionary texts that
were taken and preserved.

00:22:21.780 --> 00:22:23.760
And from this, they
were able to reconstruct

00:22:23.760 --> 00:22:25.740
what the language
must have been.

00:22:25.740 --> 00:22:28.965
And it now has its first native
speaker-- Jessie Little Doe's

00:22:28.965 --> 00:22:34.310
daughter, who's a native
speaker of Wampanoag.

00:22:34.310 --> 00:22:37.900
This has revitalized the tribe.

00:22:37.900 --> 00:22:39.660
They're now studying it.

00:22:39.660 --> 00:22:41.430
They're reconstructing
their history.

00:22:41.430 --> 00:22:43.390
They're reviving.

00:22:43.390 --> 00:22:45.810
It's a pretty
amazing achievement.

00:22:45.810 --> 00:22:51.610
Jessie got her Ph.D. with
us, with Ken, her department,

00:22:51.610 --> 00:22:54.490
it's the first time this
has ever happened, I think.

00:22:54.490 --> 00:22:57.270
Now there are efforts to
do it In other places.

00:22:57.270 --> 00:23:00.690
But if you can
revive-- right now,

00:23:00.690 --> 00:23:04.140
there's enormous
destruction going on.

00:23:04.140 --> 00:23:07.030
Species destruction,
for example,

00:23:07.030 --> 00:23:10.430
is taking place at a
level that hasn't happened

00:23:10.430 --> 00:23:15.030
for 65 million years,
literally-- the time

00:23:15.030 --> 00:23:18.280
when an asteroid hit
the earth, apparently,

00:23:18.280 --> 00:23:24.191
and wiped out the dinosaurs, and
the majority of living species

00:23:24.191 --> 00:23:25.180
were destroyed.

00:23:25.180 --> 00:23:26.780
Mammals survived.

00:23:26.780 --> 00:23:28.840
That's why we're around.

00:23:28.840 --> 00:23:32.640
But, right now, the
same thing's happening.

00:23:32.640 --> 00:23:36.220
Species destruction is
happening, about at that level.

00:23:36.220 --> 00:23:38.950
And now, we're the
asteroid, of course.

00:23:38.950 --> 00:23:43.310
We're destroying the
species at a massive rate.

00:23:43.310 --> 00:23:45.160
Language destruction
is kind of a little

00:23:45.160 --> 00:23:48.780
like that at a cultural
and human level.

00:23:48.780 --> 00:23:53.806
You're destroying the
richness of human civilization

00:23:53.806 --> 00:23:55.840
and understanding of the world.

00:23:55.840 --> 00:23:57.715
It's disappearing fast.

00:23:57.715 --> 00:24:00.350
It's disappearing
in Europe-- not just

00:24:00.350 --> 00:24:02.210
in indigenous cultures.

00:24:02.210 --> 00:24:04.360
So if you go to,
say, Italy, there

00:24:04.360 --> 00:24:05.770
are people all
over the place who

00:24:05.770 --> 00:24:07.910
can't talk to
their grandmothers.

00:24:07.910 --> 00:24:10.410
The grandmothers speak
a different language.

00:24:10.410 --> 00:24:12.400
They're called dialects,
but they're actually

00:24:12.400 --> 00:24:14.010
different languages.

00:24:14.010 --> 00:24:15.780
The number of
languages in Europe

00:24:15.780 --> 00:24:21.170
has contracted radically
over recent years

00:24:21.170 --> 00:24:23.980
through the policies
of state formation.

00:24:23.980 --> 00:24:27.120
When states are formed,
the formation of states

00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:30.060
is an extremely violent process.

00:24:30.060 --> 00:24:36.832
It imposes a rigid
form on societies,

00:24:36.832 --> 00:24:38.540
bringing together
people who have nothing

00:24:38.540 --> 00:24:40.200
to do with each
other, and separating

00:24:40.200 --> 00:24:43.100
people who have everything
to do with each other.

00:24:43.100 --> 00:24:46.530
That's why Europe was
the most savage place

00:24:46.530 --> 00:24:50.730
in the world for centuries while
the process of state formation

00:24:50.730 --> 00:24:52.220
was taking place.

00:24:52.220 --> 00:24:54.970
You look around the world
today, and just about

00:24:54.970 --> 00:25:00.320
every major conflict is based
on the imperial borders.

00:25:00.320 --> 00:25:03.360
Borders were imposed
by the imperial powers

00:25:03.360 --> 00:25:07.370
for their own interests,
forming states

00:25:07.370 --> 00:25:11.800
which have no significance
for most of the people.

00:25:11.800 --> 00:25:14.640
So take, say, Pakistan
and Afghanistan.

00:25:14.640 --> 00:25:18.400
We talk about terrorists
crossing Pakistan

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:20.090
to Afghanistan.

00:25:20.090 --> 00:25:24.330
They are, many of them,
