We deport them.

00:27:44.800 --> 00:27:46.870
That's a state border.

00:27:46.870 --> 00:27:48.500
That's the way borders work.

00:27:48.500 --> 00:27:51.050
All over the world,
that's the way it works.

00:27:51.050 --> 00:27:53.750
Take a look at the horror
stories all of the world.

00:27:53.750 --> 00:27:57.420
Almost entirely, the result
of the imposition of state

00:27:57.420 --> 00:28:00.240
borders, which also
has the consequence

00:28:00.240 --> 00:28:02.590
of wiping out lots of languages.

00:28:02.590 --> 00:28:06.380
When you impose a state
border, it constitutes, say,

00:28:06.380 --> 00:28:10.580
France, or Italy, or
Germany, or Guatemala,

00:28:10.580 --> 00:28:14.060
or whatever it may be, or the
United States for that matter,

00:28:14.060 --> 00:28:16.950
you're wiping out huge
numbers of languages

00:28:16.950 --> 00:28:18.760
which are internal to them.

00:28:18.760 --> 00:28:22.820
Well, this is a kind of--
it's not species destruction,

00:28:22.820 --> 00:28:24.745
but it's kind of
analogous to it.

00:28:24.745 --> 00:28:26.940
And it's going on all the time.

00:28:26.940 --> 00:28:33.640
And the effort to save species,
cultures, societies, languages

00:28:33.640 --> 00:28:35.260
is a major effort.

00:28:35.260 --> 00:28:37.120
Happening in Europe, too.

00:28:37.120 --> 00:28:40.290
So right now
there's a referendum

00:28:40.290 --> 00:28:42.080
coming up in Catalonia.

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:47.740
Another one in Scotland
asking about autonomy,

00:28:47.740 --> 00:28:49.180
or independence.

00:28:49.180 --> 00:28:53.350
That's dissolving the European
state system, something

00:28:53.350 --> 00:28:55.590
which has been
going on for awhile,

00:28:55.590 --> 00:28:57.840
and reconstructing
the languages.

00:28:57.840 --> 00:29:02.710
Actually, I visited
Barcelona in the late '70s.

00:29:02.710 --> 00:29:05.180
You couldn't hear
a word of Catalan.

00:29:05.180 --> 00:29:08.820
It was spoken, but secret,
because under the dictatorship,

00:29:08.820 --> 00:29:11.930
which the US backed,
it was barred.

00:29:11.930 --> 00:29:14.010
10 years later, if
you go to Catalonia,

00:29:14.010 --> 00:29:15.890
all you hear is Catalan.

00:29:15.890 --> 00:29:17.890
It revived.

00:29:17.890 --> 00:29:21.170
The Basque languages revived.

00:29:21.170 --> 00:29:24.030
Other regional
languages are reviving.

00:29:24.030 --> 00:29:27.510
If you walk around Wales,
kids walking out of school

00:29:27.510 --> 00:29:30.190
are talking Welsh.

00:29:30.190 --> 00:29:32.710
Things like this are happening.

00:29:32.710 --> 00:29:36.880
Ken's achievement
was unique, but it's

00:29:36.880 --> 00:29:39.520
a kind of a natural development.

00:29:39.520 --> 00:29:41.990
I think it should be
stimulated myself.

00:29:41.990 --> 00:29:44.380
But we should
recognize that there's

00:29:44.380 --> 00:29:51.110
enormous loss when the cultural
wealth of a society disappears.

00:29:51.110 --> 00:29:53.600
That's encapsulated
crucially in its language.

00:29:57.672 --> 00:29:58.630
INTERVIEWER: All right.

00:29:58.630 --> 00:30:00.630
So I'm going to change
gears a little bit again.

00:30:00.630 --> 00:30:02.290
Can you comment on
the contribution

00:30:02.290 --> 00:30:05.550
of research and statistical
natural language processing

00:30:05.550 --> 00:30:07.520
to linguistics?

00:30:07.520 --> 00:30:10.650
And that's a yes/no question,
I realize, but-- OK.

00:30:10.650 --> 00:30:12.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:12.490 --> 00:30:14.910
NOAM CHOMSKY: One of the
early proponents of it,

00:30:14.910 --> 00:30:19.630
maybe the earliest
in 1955, when I

00:30:19.630 --> 00:30:21.190
was working on
linguistic theory,

00:30:21.190 --> 00:30:25.290
it seemed to me the
only possible way

00:30:25.290 --> 00:30:30.900
in which a, let's say, a
child, could identify words

00:30:30.900 --> 00:30:35.310
in continuous text-- you know,
you're not hearing single words

00:30:35.310 --> 00:30:36.520
when you live in the world.

00:30:36.520 --> 00:30:39.190
You're hearing continuous text.

00:30:39.190 --> 00:30:41.600
It seemed to me the only
way that is could be done

00:30:41.600 --> 00:30:50.230
was by detecting transitional
probabilities of sounds

00:30:50.230 --> 00:30:53.030
or syllables.

00:30:53.030 --> 00:30:56.930
If you get to a word
boundary, the predictability

00:30:56.930 --> 00:31:01.330
of the next sound is lower
than if you're inside a word.

00:31:01.330 --> 00:31:01.930
Right?

00:31:01.930 --> 00:31:03.450
For obvious reasons.

00:31:03.450 --> 00:31:05.840
So if you check these
transitional probabilities,

00:31:05.840 --> 00:31:09.590
it looked as if you ought
to be able to detect words.

00:31:09.590 --> 00:31:12.640
That's probably
the first proposal.

00:31:12.640 --> 00:31:15.840
Maybe the first
proposal of literature.

00:31:15.840 --> 00:31:18.690
It turns out not to be accurate.

00:31:18.690 --> 00:31:20.900
Just in the last
couple of years,

00:31:20.900 --> 00:31:23.250
there's been some
really careful work

00:31:23.250 --> 00:31:28.200
on statistical
analysis of texts.

00:31:28.200 --> 00:31:31.960
Charles Yang, who got
his Ph.D. At MIT-- he's

00:31:31.960 --> 00:31:34.712
now at Penn, a computational
linguist cognitive

00:31:34.712 --> 00:31:39.270
scientist-- he showed
that if you actually

00:31:39.270 --> 00:31:42.610
use this technique on connected
text, that what you get

00:31:42.610 --> 00:31:45.640
is syllables, not words.

00:31:45.640 --> 00:31:47.190
So that doesn't work.

00:31:47.190 --> 00:31:51.870
He also pointed out that if
you add a linguistic principle,

00:31:51.870 --> 00:31:54.820
you do get a better
approximation to words.

00:31:54.820 --> 00:32:00.100
Linguistic principle is that
a word-- well, real words,

00:32:00.100 --> 00:32:02.460
tend to have stress
peak within them--

00:32:02.460 --> 00:32:04.730
stress pitch peek inside them.

00:32:04.730 --> 00:32:07.010
So if you add that
principle, and then you

00:32:07.010 --> 00:32:10.470
do the statistical analysis,
you get a better approximation.

00:32:10.470 --> 00:32:15.150
There's subsequent work by a
number of cognitive scientists

00:32:15.150 --> 00:32:19.350
which has shown
that if you add what

00:32:19.350 --> 00:32:23.390
are called the prosodic
structure-- the whole pitch

00:32:23.390 --> 00:32:27.800
stress structure of a
sentence-- it goes up and down,

00:32:27.800 --> 00:32:30.730
but really reflecting
phrases pretty much,

00:32:30.730 --> 00:32:32.380
if you look at the
pitch structure.

00:32:32.380 --> 00:32:34.330
If you add all of
that, and then you

00:32:34.330 --> 00:32:36.160
do the statistical
analysis, you get

00:32:36.160 --> 00:32:38.470
and even better approximation.

00:32:38.470 --> 00:32:42.770
Now this is one of the very
few cases where there's

00:32:42.770 --> 00:32:47.300
any results from
statistical analysis.

00:32:47.300 --> 00:32:52.690
There has been-- there's
a kind of a industry

00:32:52.690 --> 00:32:57.890
in computational cognitive
science and computer

00:32:57.890 --> 00:33:00.810
science trying to
show that you can

00:33:00.810 --> 00:33:04.480
get significant
knowledge of a language

00:33:04.480 --> 00:33:08.100
by statistical analysis of text.

00:33:08.100 --> 00:33:12.710
Antecedently, that's
extremely unlikely to succeed.

00:33:12.710 --> 00:33:16.450
You do not get discoveries
in the sciences

00:33:16.450 --> 00:33:22.030
by taking huge amounts of data,
throwing them into a computer,

00:33:22.030 --> 00:33:24.860
and doing statistical
analysis of them.

00:33:24.860 --> 00:33:27.900
Try to think it through in
the history of the sciences.

00:33:27.900 --> 00:33:29.910
It just doesn't happen.

00:33:29.910 --> 00:33:32.840
That's not the way
you understand things.

00:33:32.840 --> 00:33:35.490
You have to have
theoretical insights.

00:33:35.490 --> 00:33:37.290
You have to know what
kind of experiments

00:33:37.290 --> 00:33:40.580
to carry out-- what kind of
data are worth looking at,

00:33:40.580 --> 00:33:43.170
which kind of throw
away, and so on.

00:33:43.170 --> 00:33:45.950
That's the way the sciences
have always worked.

00:33:45.950 --> 00:33:49.860
If you wanted to, say,
study the laws of motion,

00:33:49.860 --> 00:33:52.700
you could take a huge
number of videotapes

00:33:52.700 --> 00:33:55.050
of what's happening
outside the window,

00:33:55.050 --> 00:33:59.380
and subject them to
statistical analysis.

00:33:59.380 --> 00:34:01.360
You could get a
pretty good prediction

00:34:01.360 --> 00:34:04.296
of the next thing that's going
to happen outside the window--

00:34:04.296 --> 00:34:05.920
actually, a better
prediction than what

00:34:05.920 --> 00:34:08.150
the physics department can give.

00:34:08.150 --> 00:34:10.710
But it's not science.

00:34:10.710 --> 00:34:17.020
It's a way of matching data, and
maybe predicting some new data.

00:34:17.020 --> 00:34:19.440
But that's not what
understanding is.

00:34:19.440 --> 00:34:22.409
And it's very unlikely to
work for language, either.

00:34:22.409 --> 00:34:25.840
And I think the record shows
that it really fails totally.

00:34:25.840 --> 00:34:27.730
I could run through examples.

00:34:27.730 --> 00:34:30.790
But every example that's
been carefully studied,

00:34:30.790 --> 00:34:34.770
it simply doesn't work,
for pretty much the reasons

00:34:34.770 --> 00:34:38.850
that Charles Yang and his
successors discovered.

00:34:38.850 --> 00:34:43.040
You have to have the-- have to
understand the principles that

00:34:43.040 --> 00:34:47.204
determine what
underlies the system.

00:34:47.204 --> 00:34:49.620
And then if you look around
the edges of those principles,

00:34:49.620 --> 00:34:53.480
you can find some sometimes
useful statistical data.

00:34:53.480 --> 00:34:56.139
I think that's probably the
way it's going to continue,

00:34:56.139 --> 00:34:58.300
but certainly is the
way it has so far.

00:35:00.622 --> 00:35:02.580
INTERVIEWER: We're going
to change gears again.

00:35:02.580 --> 00:35:05.190
What, in your opinion, are
the most effective strategies

00:35:05.190 --> 00:35:08.836
for building a more and
just peace-- I'm sorry,

00:35:08.836 --> 00:35:11.460
start over again-- for building
a more just and peaceful world,

00:35:11.460 --> 00:35:14.100
and in your view, what are the
best-- the most significant

00:35:14.100 --> 00:35:16.800
takeaways-- from
Occupy the Arabs bring,

00:35:16.800 --> 00:35:20.540
and the Ukrainian
Euromaiden uprising.

00:35:20.540 --> 00:35:24.520
NOAM CHOMSKY: Well, those are
all quite different events,

00:35:24.520 --> 00:35:29.660
and I don't think you
can consolidate them.

00:35:29.660 --> 00:35:33.460
Over time, there has--
you know, history

00:35:33.460 --> 00:35:36.600
doesn't just go in
a straight line.

00:35:36.600 --> 00:35:39.090
There's progress,
there's regression.

00:35:39.090 --> 00:35:41.650
And they're often in parallel.

00:35:41.650 --> 00:35:46.910
So say, take the last say, 50,
60 years in the United States.

00:35:46.910 --> 00:35:48.730
There's been
significant progress

00:35:48.730 --> 00:35:54.410
in developing a more peaceful
and just and equitable society.

00:35:54.410 --> 00:35:57.810
Probably the most dramatic
example is women's rights.

00:35:57.810 --> 00:36:01.400
Totally different from what
it was 50 or 60 years ago.

00:36:01.400 --> 00:36:03.430
It may be kind of
hard to remember,

00:36:03.430 --> 00:36:07.820
but if you look at US
history, at the time

00:36:07.820 --> 00:36:12.540
of the American Revolution,
the women were not people.

00:36:12.540 --> 00:36:14.110
They were property.

00:36:14.110 --> 00:36:18.020
The United States took
over British common law.

00:36:18.020 --> 00:36:20.720
And under British
common law, a woman

00:36:20.720 --> 00:36:24.050
is the property of
her father, and it's

00:36:24.050 --> 00:36:26.590
transferred to her husband.

00:36:26.590 --> 00:36:29.500
So for example, one of the
arguments against giving women

00:36:29.500 --> 00:36:34.330
votes was that it would be
unfair to unmarried men,

00:36:34.330 --> 00:36:38.380
because a married man would
have two votes, since obviously

00:36:38.380 --> 00:36:42.480
the property votes the
way the owner votes.

00:36:42.480 --> 00:36:44.760
That was US law.

00:36:44.760 --> 00:36:48.130
If you look at the
chipping away of this,

00:36:48.130 --> 00:36:53.760
it literally was not until
1975 that this principle

00:36:53.760 --> 00:36:55.320
was abandoned.

00:36:55.320 --> 00:37:00.300
in 1975, the Supreme Court
ruled that women have the right

00:37:00.300 --> 00:37:04.610
to serve as peers
in federal jury.

00:37:04.610 --> 00:37:07.860
Peer means a person
just like you.

00:37:07.860 --> 00:37:12.130
OK, that goes back to the Magna
Carta in the 13th century.

00:37:12.130 --> 00:37:17.740
Women were accepted as
peers legally in 1975.

00:37:17.740 --> 00:37:20.340
Now that was part of
a major change that's

00:37:20.340 --> 00:37:25.200
taken place in American
culture since the 1960s--

00:37:25.200 --> 00:37:28.240
one of the main outgrowths
of '60s activism.

00:37:28.240 --> 00:37:30.570
And there are plenty of
other things like it.

00:37:30.570 --> 00:37:34.060
So opposition to, say,
violent aggression

00:37:34.060 --> 00:37:39.750
is far above what it
was 50 or 60 years ago.

00:37:39.750 --> 00:37:44.350
Take, say, Kennedy's
invasion of South Vietnam.

00:37:44.350 --> 00:37:47.100
It's a phrase you've
never heard, I suppose,

00:37:47.100 --> 00:37:49.870
because it isn't
in consciousness.

00:37:49.870 --> 00:37:53.210
It happened in the world,
but it wasn't reported

00:37:53.210 --> 00:37:56.080
and it isn't part
of American history.

00:37:56.080 --> 00:38:00.560
In the 1962, Kennedy sent
the American Air Force

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:03.270
to start bombing South Vietnam.

00:38:03.270 --> 00:38:07.160
Authorized chemical
warfare to destroy crops,

00:38:07.160 --> 00:38:10.470
so to drive the people
out of the countryside.

00:38:10.470 --> 00:38:13.111
Began big programs to
concentrate people, and put

00:38:13.111 --> 00:38:15.550
them out at the
concentration camps,

00:38:15.550 --> 00:38:19.420
to prevent them from supporting
the guerrilla movement, which

00:38:19.420 --> 00:38:22.660
was overthrowing the US
installed government.

00:38:22.660 --> 00:38:25.340
That's an invasion.

00:38:25.340 --> 00:38:28.520
It happened, but not
in our consciousness.

00:38:28.520 --> 00:38:30.230
The reason it's not
in our consciousness

00:38:30.230 --> 00:38:32.380
is there was no opposition.

00:38:32.380 --> 00:38:33.340
It was recorded.

00:38:33.340 --> 00:38:34.590
It was kind of known.

00:38:34.590 --> 00:38:38.680
You know, like it wasn't a
total secret, but nobody cared.

00:38:38.680 --> 00:38:40.812
You couldn't get people
to talk about it.

00:38:40.812 --> 00:38:42.270
I mean, literally
I remember trying

00:38:42.270 --> 00:38:46.890
to give talks in the early
'60s in people's living rooms.

00:38:46.890 --> 00:38:49.650
You could get more people
than that together.

00:38:49.650 --> 00:38:52.530
Well that was the early '60s.

00:38:52.530 --> 00:38:59.208
In 2003, the United
States invaded Iraq.

00:38:59.208 --> 00:39:03.880
It's the first time in the
history of the imperial world

00:39:03.880 --> 00:39:09.420
that there have been massive
protests prior to the invasion,

00:39:09.420 --> 00:39:12.640
prior to the invasion-- huge
protests all of the world.

00:39:12.640 --> 00:39:15.300
Here, too.

00:39:15.300 --> 00:39:17.710
My classes were called off
because the students wanted

00:39:17.710 --> 00:39:20.610
to call them off to go
down to the demonstration.

00:39:20.610 --> 00:39:23.360
That was 2003.

00:39:23.360 --> 00:39:27.590
Well, it didn't end the
war, but it limited it.

00:39:27.590 --> 00:39:30.469
It's often believed
that the demonstrations

00:39:30.469 --> 00:39:31.260
didn't do anything.

00:39:31.260 --> 00:39:33.000
That's a mistake.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:37.030
The United States could not
begin to carry out the policies

00:39:37.030 --> 00:39:39.360
that Kennedy and
Johnson could carry out

00:39:39.360 --> 00:39:41.280
without a second thought.

00:39:41.280 --> 00:39:44.530
It was bad enough, but
it wasn't B52 bombing

00:39:44.530 --> 00:39:48.110
of heavily populated
urban centers.

00:39:48.110 --> 00:39:51.350
It wasn't chemical
warfare destroying crops.

00:39:51.350 --> 00:39:53.670
Many of the atrocities
of the Vietnam War

00:39:53.670 --> 00:39:56.020
simply couldn't be contemplated.

00:39:56.020 --> 00:39:58.090
Horrible enough, but not that.

00:39:58.090 --> 00:40:00.080
OK, all of that is progress.

00:40:00.080 --> 00:40:02.200
There's also a regression.

00:40:02.200 --> 00:40:05.510
There's been a big
backlash from power centers

00:40:05.510 --> 00:40:09.780
against the civilizing
effect of the '60s.

00:40:09.780 --> 00:40:11.870
Now, that's the
neoliberal attack

00:40:11.870 --> 00:40:15.370
on the population which has
been going on for a generation.

00:40:15.370 --> 00:40:19.870
That's why, say,
real wages, real,

00:40:19.870 --> 00:40:25.550
for male workers-- real wages
today are at the level of 1968

00:40:25.550 --> 00:40:27.770
for the general public.

00:40:27.770 --> 00:40:31.840
And real wages are about
the level of 30 years ago.

00:40:31.840 --> 00:40:35.000
There's been some
stagnation or decline

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.750
for the majority
of the population.

00:40:37.750 --> 00:40:41.770
Tremendous concentration
of wealth in tiny number

00:40:41.770 --> 00:40:44.710
of-- tiny sector
of the population.

00:40:44.710 --> 00:40:49.530
Mostly a fraction of 1%,
which feeds politics.

00:40:49.530 --> 00:40:53.170
Political power
reflects economic power.

00:40:53.170 --> 00:40:58.530
The Supreme Court just yesterday
just struck another blow

00:40:58.530 --> 00:41:01.700
against democracy and
its committed effort

00:41:01.700 --> 00:41:05.450
to try to undermine
the functioning

00:41:05.450 --> 00:41:08.470
of a democratic system
by placing power

00:41:08.470 --> 00:41:11.352
in the hands of those
who are super rich.

00:41:11.352 --> 00:41:12.870
OK, that's going on.

00:41:12.870 --> 00:41:15.960
That's the McCutcheon
case a couple days ago.

00:41:15.960 --> 00:41:17.970
Well, that's regression.

00:41:17.970 --> 00:41:20.130
And they're going
on in parallel.

00:41:20.130 --> 00:41:22.120
That's the way history works.

00:41:22.120 --> 00:41:24.130
So what's the way to go forward?

00:41:24.130 --> 00:41:27.050
Well, you know, as
Martin Luther King

00:41:27.050 --> 00:41:30.750
put it-- shift
the arc of history

00:41:30.750 --> 00:41:33.250
by your own efforts in activism.

00:41:33.250 --> 00:41:35.820
That's the only way
it's ever worked.

00:41:35.820 --> 00:41:39.629
The arc of history bends the
way we decide to bend it.

00:41:39.629 --> 00:41:41.170
INTERVIEWER: In
"Hopes and Prospects"

00:41:41.170 --> 00:41:43.470
you compare Obama and Bush II.

00:41:43.470 --> 00:41:45.350
That's four years ago.

00:41:45.350 --> 00:41:46.480
What would you say today?

00:41:51.300 --> 00:41:53.100
NOAM CHOMSKY: Like
what I just said

00:41:53.100 --> 00:41:57.870
about the arc of history--
both better in some ways, worse

00:41:57.870 --> 00:41:59.470
in others.

00:41:59.470 --> 00:42:03.400
So, for example, I
mentioned Guantanamo.

00:42:03.400 --> 00:42:06.280
Guantanamo is a
major torture center.

00:42:06.280 --> 00:42:10.480
OK, today, probably
torture isn't

00:42:10.480 --> 00:42:15.280
taking place in Guantanamo--
at least what we call torture.

00:42:15.280 --> 00:42:19.720
Remember, the United States has
a special definition of torture

00:42:19.720 --> 00:42:22.510
which is different from
the world's definition.

00:42:22.510 --> 00:42:26.480
So for example, in the
world, a solitary confinement

00:42:26.480 --> 00:42:28.730
is considered torture.

00:42:28.730 --> 00:42:31.470
You take a look at the
torture convention--

00:42:31.470 --> 00:42:33.610
international
torture convention.

00:42:33.610 --> 00:42:36.100
Solitary confinement
is regarded--

00:42:36.100 --> 00:42:38.220
and other forms of
mental torture--

00:42:38.220 --> 00:42:40.050
are regarded as torture.

00:42:40.050 --> 00:42:41.220
And they are.

00:42:41.220 --> 00:42:44.640
You try to lock yourself up in
a room for a couple of days,

00:42:44.640 --> 00:42:46.800
and you'll see what happens.

00:42:46.800 --> 00:42:48.370
So it's kind of torture.

00:42:48.370 --> 00:42:51.970
In the United States, it's
surely going on in Guantanamo.

00:42:51.970 --> 00:42:53.410
But it's also a routine.

00:42:53.410 --> 00:42:56.290
It goes on in the
prisons all the time.

00:42:56.290 --> 00:42:58.280
You go to the maximum
security prisons,

00:42:58.280 --> 00:43:00.820
they are torture chambers.

00:43:00.820 --> 00:43:06.900
People are confined 23
hours a day in a small room.

00:43:06.900 --> 00:43:09.850
It drives you insane.

