00:52:33.890 --> 00:52:36.620
Is there any systematic
effect on languages

00:52:36.620 --> 00:52:40.460
that adopted someone
else's writing system?

00:52:40.460 --> 00:52:45.400
NOAM CHOMSKY: There is a
systematic effect of literacy.

00:52:45.400 --> 00:52:47.680
It's not so much adopting
the writing system

00:52:47.680 --> 00:52:51.280
as using it for reading.

00:52:51.280 --> 00:52:54.140
So if we actually want,
there's a-- Ken Hale,

00:52:54.140 --> 00:52:57.610
same guy we talked
about before-- he

00:52:57.610 --> 00:53:02.490
did a very important study in
the 1970s in which he showed

00:53:02.490 --> 00:53:08.670
that-- an article that appeared
on what's called cultural gaps.

00:53:08.670 --> 00:53:13.080
He studied the languages that
he worked on, mostly Australian,

00:53:13.080 --> 00:53:18.380
and found that many of
them had all kind of what

00:53:18.380 --> 00:53:19.430
looked like gaps.

00:53:19.430 --> 00:53:21.600
Like, they didn't
have number words.

00:53:21.600 --> 00:53:23.369
They didn't have color words.

00:53:23.369 --> 00:53:24.910
Or they didn't have
relative clauses.

00:53:24.910 --> 00:53:27.800
A lot of other things
they didn't have.

00:53:27.800 --> 00:53:30.450
And what he showed
was that all of this

00:53:30.450 --> 00:53:32.940
was just totally superficial.

00:53:32.940 --> 00:53:35.780
The people had all the concept.

00:53:35.780 --> 00:53:38.580
They had no problem with
dealing with any of them.

00:53:38.580 --> 00:53:42.790
They used them all the time,
but just in more indirect ways.

00:53:42.790 --> 00:53:44.630
So if they didn't
have number words,

00:53:44.630 --> 00:53:49.280
they would still be
able to say five, ten.

00:53:49.280 --> 00:53:52.160
They had no problem dealing
with market societies.

00:53:52.160 --> 00:53:54.470
They may not have
had the color red,

00:53:54.470 --> 00:53:56.580
but they could say blood-like.

00:53:56.580 --> 00:53:58.980
And the same was true
even of structural things,

00:53:58.980 --> 00:54:01.260
like embedded relative clauses.

00:54:01.260 --> 00:54:03.620
Well, that was an
important study.

00:54:03.620 --> 00:54:06.450
Ignored, like most
important studies.

00:54:06.450 --> 00:54:11.060
But, shortly after it, somebody
else in our department, Wayne

00:54:11.060 --> 00:54:15.480
O'Neil, another friend
of Anne's and mine,

00:54:15.480 --> 00:54:18.080
who studies the
history of English,

00:54:18.080 --> 00:54:21.510
he did a study of
middle English.

00:54:21.510 --> 00:54:24.490
And he investigated, and if
he was looking for something

00:54:24.490 --> 00:54:30.460
similar, he discovered that the
use of complex constructions,

00:54:30.460 --> 00:54:34.140
which had embedded
elements in them,

00:54:34.140 --> 00:54:37.840
increased as literacy increased.

00:54:37.840 --> 00:54:40.290
There's a natural
reason for that.

00:54:40.290 --> 00:54:42.900
When you speak,
you're constrained

00:54:42.900 --> 00:54:47.950
by short term memory,
which is pretty small.

00:54:47.950 --> 00:54:50.920
Short term memory is around
seven or something like that.

00:54:50.920 --> 00:54:53.560
The same for humans
and other organisms.

00:54:53.560 --> 00:54:56.060
And that means
you can't do much.

00:54:56.060 --> 00:54:59.920
So ordinary speech tends to
be what's called para-tactic.

00:54:59.920 --> 00:55:03.070
You just kind of tack things
on one after the other,

00:55:03.070 --> 00:55:06.550
because you can't embed.

00:55:06.550 --> 00:55:10.400
On the other hand, once
you move to literacy,

00:55:10.400 --> 00:55:16.990
you begin to use capacities that
you always had but never used.

00:55:16.990 --> 00:55:21.560
It's like, when
the people learn.

00:55:21.560 --> 00:55:24.220
You go to school and, you
say, first grade or something,

00:55:24.220 --> 00:55:26.200
and they teach you
how to multiply.

00:55:26.200 --> 00:55:30.600
You begin to use a capacity
which you always had.

00:55:30.600 --> 00:55:32.190
It's not taught.

00:55:32.190 --> 00:55:35.430
It's part of your
intrinsic capacities

00:55:35.430 --> 00:55:38.300
that you have the
capacity for number.

00:55:38.300 --> 00:55:40.240
Every society has it.

00:55:40.240 --> 00:55:42.410
Every human being has it.

00:55:42.410 --> 00:55:47.680
It's kind of a mystery that
bothered Darwin and Wallace--

00:55:47.680 --> 00:55:49.790
the founders of
evolutionary theory.

00:55:49.790 --> 00:55:53.440
They asked, how could it
evolve since it's never used?

00:55:53.440 --> 00:55:55.280
But it's true that
everyone has it.

00:55:55.280 --> 00:55:58.410
But you can't do
it in your head.

00:55:58.410 --> 00:56:01.764
Like, you can't multiply
big numbers in your head.

00:56:01.764 --> 00:56:02.550
Right?

00:56:02.550 --> 00:56:05.820
You'd collapse after
a very short period.

00:56:05.820 --> 00:56:08.630
But you can multiply them
once you learn the technique,

00:56:08.630 --> 00:56:10.380
because you've
got the knowledge.

00:56:10.380 --> 00:56:12.210
You just have to exhibit it.

00:56:12.210 --> 00:56:14.920
And the same thing
happens with literacy.

00:56:14.920 --> 00:56:18.450
Once literacy spreads,
you get much more complex

00:56:18.450 --> 00:56:22.440
linguistic usage, even in
speech, because it carries over

00:56:22.440 --> 00:56:24.090
from writing to speech.

00:56:24.090 --> 00:56:27.720
So that effect I think
